1. Our Perception Band Is Extremely Narrow

Take electromagnetic radiation.

Humans see only the visible spectrum.

gamma rays
x-rays
ultraviolet
VISIBLE LIGHT
infrared
microwaves
radio waves

Visible light is a very small window in that entire range.

Yet many organisms perceive outside it:
	•	bees see ultraviolet
	•	snakes detect infrared
	•	some animals sense magnetic fields

So even in something as basic as light, our “reality” is a narrow slice.

⸻

2. The Same Is True for Time

Human perception operates roughly in the range of:

milliseconds → decades

But physical processes span:

nanoseconds → billions of years

Things happening too fast or too slow are effectively invisible to us without instruments.

⸻

3. The Same Is True for Scale

Our intuition works best for objects roughly between:

millimeters → kilometers

But reality also contains:
	•	quantum particles
	•	molecular machines
	•	planetary systems
	•	galaxies
	•	cosmic structures

Again, our natural perception band is tiny.

⸻

4. Intelligence Might Also Have Bands

Your point about intelligence not appearing within our perception band is interesting.

Human intelligence has certain characteristics:
	•	symbolic language
	•	tool use
	•	cumulative culture
	•	large-scale coordination

But intelligence could exist in forms that don’t resemble this.

Possible examples scientists discuss include:
	•	distributed intelligence in ecosystems
	•	collective intelligence in insect colonies
	•	machine intelligence
	•	large-scale network cognition

These may operate differently enough that we don’t recognize them easily.

